    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Clear air turbulence, or CAT, can be a bit of a tricky beast to track, much like a goblin hiding in plain sight. You see, CAT is essentially pockets of turbulent air that form in the atmosphere, often without any visible signs of weather, like a goblin's lair hidden behind a waterfall. Radar systems, which rely on the reflection of radio waves off particles in the air, have a hard time detecting these invisible pockets of turbulence because they don't reflect radar waves like a thunderstorm would. It's like trying to spot a goblin in a crowded market - they might be there, but they're not exactly broadcasting their presence. \n\nThat being said, modern radar systems are getting better at detecting CAT, and some specialized radar systems can even use advanced algorithms to identify areas of turbulence. But even with these advancements, CAT can still be a bit of a challenge to track, much like a goblin trying to evade a group of hunters.",
